Merulus a monk‚ devoted to tears and prayers and psalmody‚ saw in a vision a crown of white flowers deseending from heaven on his head. Fourteen years after his death tanta...de...sepulchro illius fragrantia suauitatis emanauit, ac si illic florum omnium fuissent odora· 15 menta congregata. Sometimes the fragrant odour is related to have ’ been perceived at the time of death. Thus at the death of a certain Servulus it is related (Aelfric Hom 11 98) “Then was the house filled with a wondrous odour so that all the corpsebearers were filled with the winsome fragrance and the odours ceased not in their nostrils till the 20 holy body was buried ''. Similarly at the death of the nun Romula (ibid 548). A like fragrance is said to have pervaded the whole island of Crowland after the death of St Guthlac Goodwin pp 86—90.
